body:
Recording for reference after some discussion related to #7130 

Neither scheduling, nor V3Split (and possibly other passes) understand assignments through a virtual interface variable to an interface member:

```systemverilog
IFace iface();
virtual IFace viface = iface;

always @(posedge clk) begin
   iface.foo <= '0;
end

always @(posedge clk) begin
   viface.foo <= '1;
end
```

While this is dubious code, if `foo` is wide and not updated atomically, in multi-threaded mode it can end up in an arbitrary mixed state as the OrderGraph only tracks `viface`, which is an unrelated variable, while the write is to `iface.foo`.

Even worse, this has defined semantics in SV (if a bit dubious code still, but latest should win), but due to block splitting in V3Split, it can be scheduled in the reverse order.

```systemverilog
always @(posedge clk) begin
   iface.foo <= '0;
   viface.foo <= '1;
end
```

Similar issues exist when multiple virtual interface variables reference the same interface instance.

@micprog in case you need to reference the issue in text, e.g. any new tests added for #7130.

